tween university language teachers’ beliefs about codeswitching and their classroom practice. Each chapter investigates the extent of, and motivations for, codeswitching in one or two particular contexts, and the interactive and pedagogical functions for which alternative languages are used. Many teachers, and policy-makers, in schools as well as universities, may rethink existing ’English-only’ policies in the light of the findings reported in this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCode switching (Linguistics) 0aCode switching (Linguistics)vCase studies. 0aCode switching (Linguistics). 0aCollege studentszAsiaxLanguage. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Higher)xForeign speakers. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / English as a Second Language.2bisacsh  aEast Asia.  aEnglish language.  acodeswitching.  amedium of instruction.  ateacher cognition.  auniversity classrooms.  auniversity teachers.1 aAbdullah, Ain Nadzimah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCanh, Le Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Moyra Sweetnam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhani, Dayangku Liyana Putri Pengiran Abdul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaji-Othman, Noor Azam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamied, Fuad Abdul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeng, Chan Swee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitam, Saidai Haji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphries, Simon, 